sec-array-constructor.name: Array
sec-array-constructor.summary: The Array() constructor is used to create Array objects.
sec-array-constructor.title: Array() constructor

sec-array.prototype.concat.name: concat
sec-array.prototype.concat.summary: The concat() method is used to merge two or more arrays. This method does not change the existing arrays, but instead returns a new array.
sec-array.prototype.concat.title: Array.prototype.concat()

sec-array.prototype.copywithin.name: copyWithin
sec-array.prototype.copywithin.summary: The copyWithin() method shallow copies part of an array to another location in the same array and returns it without modifying its length.
sec-array.prototype.copywithin.title: Array.prototype.copyWithin()

sec-array.prototype.entries.name: entries
sec-array.prototype.entries.summary: The entries() method returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the key/value pairs for each index in the array.
sec-array.prototype.entries.title: Array.prototype.entries()

sec-array.prototype.every.name: every
sec-array.prototype.every.summary: The every() method tests whether all elements in the array pass the test implemented by the provided function. It returns a Boolean value.
sec-array.prototype.every.title: Array.prototype.every()

sec-array.prototype.fill.name: fill
sec-array.prototype.fill.summary: The fill() method changes all elements in an array to a static value, from a start index (default 0) to an end index (default array.length). It returns the modified array.
sec-array.prototype.fill.title: Array.prototype.fill()

sec-array.prototype.filter.name: filter
sec-array.prototype.filter.summary: The filter() method creates a new array with all elements that pass the test implemented by the provided function.
sec-array.prototype.filter.title: Array.prototype.filter()

sec-array.prototype.find.name: find
sec-array.prototype.find.summary: The find() method returns the value of the first element in the provided array that satisfies the provided testing function.
sec-array.prototype.find.title: Array.prototype.find()

sec-array.prototype.findindex.name: findIndex
sec-array.prototype.findindex.summary: The findIndex() method returns the index of the first element in the array that satisfies the provided testing function. Otherwise, it returns -1, indicating that no element passed the test.
sec-array.prototype.findindex.title: Array.prototype.findIndex()

sec-array.prototype.flat.name: flat
sec-array.prototype.flat.summary: The flat() method creates a new array with all sub-array elements concatenated into it recursively up to the specified depth.
sec-array.prototype.flat.title: Array.prototype.flat()

sec-array.prototype.flatmap.name: flatMap
sec-array.prototype.flatmap.summary: The flatMap() method first maps each element using a mapping function, then flattens the result into a new array. It is identical to a map() followed by a flat() of depth 1, but flatMap() is often quite useful, as merging both into one method is slightly more efficient.
sec-array.prototype.flatmap.title: Array.prototype.flatMap()

sec-array.prototype.foreach.name: forEach
sec-array.prototype.foreach.summary: The forEach() method executes a provided function once for each array element.
sec-array.prototype.foreach.title: Array.prototype.forEach()

sec-array.from.name: from
sec-array.from.summary: The Array.from() static method creates a new, shallow-copied Array instance from an array-like or iterable object.
sec-array.from.title: Array.from()

sec-array.prototype.includes.name: includes
sec-array.prototype.includes.summary: The includes() method determines whether an array includes a certain value among its entries, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-array.prototype.includes.title: Array.prototype.includes()

sec-array.prototype.indexof.name: indexOf
sec-array.prototype.indexof.summary: The indexOf() method returns the first index at which a given element can be found in the array, or -1 if it is not present.
sec-array.prototype.indexof.title: Array.prototype.indexOf()

sec-array.isarray.name: isArray
sec-array.isarray.summary: The Array.isArray() method determines whether the passed value is an Array.
sec-array.isarray.title: Array.isArray()

sec-array.prototype.join.name: join
sec-array.prototype.join.summary: The join() method creates and returns a new string by concatenating all of the elements in an array (or an array-like object), separated by commas or a specified separator string. If the array has only one item, then that item will be returned without using the separator.
sec-array.prototype.join.title: Array.prototype.join()

sec-array.prototype.keys.name: keys
sec-array.prototype.keys.summary: The keys() method returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the keys for each index in the array.
sec-array.prototype.keys.title: Array.prototype.keys()

sec-array.prototype.lastindexof.name: lastIndexOf
sec-array.prototype.lastindexof.summary: The lastIndexOf() method returns the last index at which a given element can be found in the array, or -1 if it is not present. The array is searched backwards, starting at fromIndex.
sec-array.prototype.lastindexof.title: Array.prototype.lastIndexOf()

sec-properties-of-array-instances-length.name: length
sec-properties-of-array-instances-length.summary: The length property of an object which is an instance of type Array sets or returns the number of elements in that array. The value is an unsigned, 32-bit integer that is always numerically greater than the highest index in the array.
sec-properties-of-array-instances-length.title: Array.prototype.length

sec-array.prototype.map.name: map
sec-array.prototype.map.summary: The map() method creates a new array populated with the results of calling a provided function on every element in the calling array.
sec-array.prototype.map.title: Array.prototype.map()

sec-array.of.name: of
sec-array.of.summary: The Array.of() method creates a new Array instance from a variable number of arguments, regardless of number or type of the arguments.
sec-array.of.title: Array.of()

sec-array.prototype.pop.name: pop
sec-array.prototype.pop.summary: The pop() method removes the last element from an array and returns that element. This method changes the length of the array.
sec-array.prototype.pop.title: Array.prototype.pop()

sec-array.prototype.push.name: push
sec-array.prototype.push.summary: The push() method adds zero or more elements to the end of an array and returns the new length of the array.
sec-array.prototype.push.title: Array.prototype.push()

sec-array.prototype.reduce.name: reduce
sec-array.prototype.reduce.summary: The reduce() method executes a reducer function (that you provide) on each element of the array, resulting in single output value.
sec-array.prototype.reduce.title: Array.prototype.reduce()

sec-array.prototype.reduceright.name: reduceRight
sec-array.prototype.reduceright.summary: The reduceRight() method applies a function against an accumulator and each value of the array (from right-to-left) to reduce it to a single value.
sec-array.prototype.reduceright.title: Array.prototype.reduceRight()

sec-array.prototype.reverse.name: reverse
sec-array.prototype.reverse.summary: The reverse() method reverses an array in place. The first array element becomes the last, and the last array element becomes the first.
sec-array.prototype.reverse.title: Array.prototype.reverse()

sec-array.prototype.shift.name: shift
sec-array.prototype.shift.summary: The shift() method removes the first element from an array and returns that removed element. This method changes the length of the array.
sec-array.prototype.shift.title: Array.prototype.shift()

sec-array.prototype.slice.name: slice
sec-array.prototype.slice.summary: The slice() method returns a shallow copy of a portion of an array into a new array object selected from start to end (end not included) where start and end represent the index of items in that array. The original array will not be modified.
sec-array.prototype.slice.title: Array.prototype.slice()

sec-array.prototype.some.name: some
sec-array.prototype.some.summary: The some() method tests whether at least one element in the array passes the test implemented by the provided function. It returns a Boolean value.
sec-array.prototype.some.title: Array.prototype.some()

sec-array.prototype.sort.name: sort
sec-array.prototype.sort.summary: The sort() method sorts the elements of an array in place and returns the sorted array. The default sort order is ascending, built upon converting the elements into strings, then comparing their sequences of UTF-16 code units values.
sec-array.prototype.sort.title: Array.prototype.sort()

sec-array.prototype.splice.name: splice
sec-array.prototype.splice.summary: The splice() method changes the contents of an array by removing or replacing existing elements and/or adding new elements in place.

ie.notes: From Internet Explorer 5.5 through 8, all elements of the array will not be deleted if deleteCount is omitted. This behavior was fixed in Internet Explorer 9.

sec-array.prototype.splice.title: Array.prototype.splice()

sec-array.prototype.tolocalestring.name: toLocaleString
sec-array.prototype.tolocalestring.summary: The toLocaleString() method returns a string representing the elements of the array. The elements are converted to Strings using their toLocaleString methods and these Strings are separated by a locale-specific String (such as a comma ,).
sec-array.prototype.tolocalestring.title: Array.prototype.toLocaleString()

sec-array.prototype.tostring.name: toString
sec-array.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified array and its elements.
sec-array.prototype.tostring.title: Array.prototype.toString()

sec-array.prototype.unshift.name: unshift
sec-array.prototype.unshift.summary: The unshift() method adds one or more elements to the beginning of an array and returns the new length of the array.
sec-array.prototype.unshift.title: Array.prototype.unshift()

sec-array.prototype.values.name: values
sec-array.prototype.values.summary: The values() method returns a new Array Iterator object that contains the values for each index in the array.

sec-array.prototype.values.title: Array.prototype.values()

sec-array.prototype-@@unscopables.name: @@unscopables

sec-get-arraybuffer.prototype.bytelength.name: byteLength
sec-get-arraybuffer.prototype.bytelength.summary: The byteLength accessor property represents the length of an ArrayBuffer in bytes.
sec-get-arraybuffer.prototype.bytelength.title: ArrayBuffer.prototype.byteLength

sec-arraybuffer.isview.name: isView
sec-arraybuffer.isview.summary: The ArrayBuffer.isView() method determines whether the passed value is one of the ArrayBuffer views, such as typed array objects or a DataView.
sec-arraybuffer.isview.title: ArrayBuffer.isView()

sec-arraybuffer.prototype.slice.name: slice
sec-arraybuffer.prototype.slice.summary: The slice() method returns a new ArrayBuffer whose contents are a copy of this ArrayBuffer's bytes from begin, inclusive, up to end, exclusive.

sec-arraybuffer-objects.name: ArrayBuffer
sec-arraybuffer-objects.summary: The ArrayBuffer object is used to represent a generic, fixed-length raw binary data buffer.
sec-arraybuffer-objects.title: ArrayBuffer

sec-async-function-objects.name: AsyncFunction
sec-async-function-objects.summary: The AsyncFunction constructor creates a new async function object. In JavaScript, every asynchronous function is actually an AsyncFunction object.
sec-async-function-objects.title: AsyncFunction

sec-number.isfinite.summary: The Number.isFinite() method determines whether the passed value is a finite number.

sec-number.isinteger.name: isInteger
sec-number.isinteger.summary: The Number.isInteger() method determines whether the passed value is an integer.

sec-number.isnan.name: isNaN
sec-number.isnan.summary: The Number.isNaN() method determines whether the passed value is NaN and its type is Number. It is a more robust version of the original, global isNaN().
sec-number.isnan.title: Number.isNaN()

sec-number.issafeinteger.name: isSafeInteger
sec-number.issafeinteger.summary: The Number.isSafeInteger() method determines whether the provided value is a number that is a safe integer.
sec-number.issafeinteger.title: Number.isSafeInteger()

sec-number.parsefloat.name: parseFloat
sec-number.parsefloat.summary: The Number.parseFloat() method parses an argument and returns a floating point number. If a number cannot be parsed from the argument, it returns NaN.
sec-number.parsefloat.title: Number.parseFloat()

sec-number.parseint.name: parseInt
sec-number.parseint.summary: The Number.parseInt() method parses a string argument and returns an integer of the specified radix or base.
sec-number.parseint.title: Number.parseInt()

sec-number.prototype.toexponential.name: toExponential
sec-number.prototype.toexponential.summary: The toExponential() method returns a string representing the Number object in exponential notation.
sec-number.prototype.toexponential.title: Number.prototype.toExponential()

sec-number.prototype.tofixed.name: toFixed
sec-number.prototype.tofixed.summary: The toFixed() method formats a number using fixed-point notation.
sec-number.prototype.tofixed.title: Number.prototype.toFixed()

sec-number.prototype.tolocalestring.name: toLocaleString
sec-number.prototype.tolocalestring.summary: The toLocaleString() method returns a string with a language-sensitive representation of this number.

ie.notes: In Internet Explorer 11, numbers are rounded to 15 decimal digits. For example, (1000000000000005).toLocaleString('en-US') returns "1,000,000,000,000,010".

sec-number.prototype.tolocalestring.title: Number.prototype.toLocaleString()

sec-number.prototype.toprecision.name: toPrecision
sec-number.prototype.toprecision.summary: The toPrecision() method returns a string representing the Number object to the specified precision.
sec-number.prototype.toprecision.title: Number.prototype.toPrecision()

sec-number.prototype.tostring.name: toString
sec-number.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified Number object.

sec-number.prototype.valueof.summary: The valueOf() method returns the wrapped primitive value of a Number object.

sec-object-constructor.name: Object
sec-object-constructor.summary: The Object constructor creates an object wrapper for the given value.

sec-object.assign.name: assign
sec-object.assign.summary: The Object.assign() method copies all enumerable own properties from one or more source objects to a target object. It returns the target object.
sec-object.assign.title: Object.assign()

sec-object.prototype.constructor.name: constructor
sec-object.prototype.constructor.summary: The constructor property returns a reference to the Object constructor function that created the instance object. Note that the value of this property is a reference to the function itself, not a string containing the function's name.
sec-object.prototype.constructor.title: Object.prototype.constructor

sec-object.create.name: create
sec-object.create.summary: The Object.create() method creates a new object, using an existing object as the prototype of the newly created object.
sec-object.create.title: Object.create()

sec-object.defineproperties.name: defineProperties
sec-object.defineproperties.summary: The Object.defineProperties() method defines new or modifies existing properties directly on an object, returning the object.
sec-object.defineproperties.title: Object.defineProperties()

sec-object.defineproperty.name: defineProperty
sec-object.defineproperty.summary: The static method Object.defineProperty() defines a new property directly on an object, or modifies an existing property on an object, and returns the object.

ie.notes: In Internet Explorer 8, this was only supported on DOM objects and with some non-standard behaviors.  This was later fixed in Internet Explorer 9.

safari.notes: Also supported in Safari 5, but not on DOM objects.

safari_ios.notes: Also supported in Safari for iOS 4.2, but not on DOM objects.

sec-object.defineproperty.title: Object.defineProperty()

sec-object.entries.name: entries
sec-object.entries.summary: The Object.entries() method returns an array of a given object's own enumerable string-keyed property [key, value] pairs, in the same order as that provided by a for...in loop. (The only important difference is that a for...in loop enumerates properties in the prototype chain as well).
sec-object.entries.title: Object.entries()

sec-object.freeze.name: freeze
sec-object.freeze.summary: The Object.freeze() method freezes an object. A frozen object can no longer be changed; freezing an object prevents new properties from being added to it, existing properties from being removed, prevents changing the enumerability, configurability, or writability of existing properties, and prevents the values of existing properties from being changed. In addition, freezing an object also prevents its prototype from being changed. freeze() returns the same object that was passed in.
sec-object.freeze.title: Object.freeze()

sec-object.fromentries.name: fromEntries
sec-object.fromentries.summary: The Object.fromEntries() method transforms a list of key-value pairs into an object.
sec-object.fromentries.title: Object.fromEntries()

sec-object.getownpropertydescriptor.name: getOwnPropertyDescriptor
sec-object.getownpropertydescriptor.summary: The Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor() method returns a property descriptor for an own property (that is, one directly present on an object and not in the object's prototype chain) of a given object.

ie.notes: In Internet Explorer 8, this was only supported on DOM objects and with some non-standard behaviors.  This was later fixed in Internet Explorer 9.

sec-object.getownpropertydescriptor.title: Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor()

sec-object.getownpropertydescriptors.name: getOwnPropertyDescriptors
sec-object.getownpropertydescriptors.summary: The Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptors() method returns all own property descriptors of a given object.
sec-object.getownpropertydescriptors.title: Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptors()

sec-object.getownpropertynames.name: getOwnPropertyNames
sec-object.getownpropertynames.summary: The Object.getOwnPropertyNames() method returns an array of all properties (including non-enumerable properties except for those which use Symbol) found directly in a given object.
sec-object.getownpropertynames.title: Object.getOwnPropertyNames()

sec-object.getownpropertysymbols.name: getOwnPropertySymbols
sec-object.getownpropertysymbols.summary: The Object.getOwnPropertySymbols() method returns an array of all symbol properties found directly upon a given object.
sec-object.getownpropertysymbols.title: Object.getOwnPropertySymbols()

sec-object.getprototypeof.name: getPrototypeOf
sec-object.getprototypeof.summary: The Object.getPrototypeOf() method returns the prototype (i.e. the value of the internal [[Prototype]] property) of the specified object.
sec-object.getprototypeof.title: Object.getPrototypeOf()

sec-object.prototype.hasownproperty.name: hasOwnProperty
sec-object.prototype.hasownproperty.summary: The hasOwnProperty() method returns a boolean indicating whether the object has the specified property as its own property (as opposed to inheriting it).
sec-object.prototype.hasownproperty.title: Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty()

sec-object.is.name: is
sec-object.is.summary: The Object.is() method determines whether two values are the same value.
sec-object.is.title: Object.is()

sec-object.isextensible.name: isExtensible
sec-object.isextensible.summary: The Object.isExtensible() method determines if an object is extensible (whether it can have new properties added to it).
sec-object.isextensible.title: Object.isExtensible()

sec-object.isfrozen.name: isFrozen
sec-object.isfrozen.summary: The Object.isFrozen() determines if an object is frozen.
sec-object.isfrozen.title: Object.isFrozen()

sec-object.prototype.isprototypeof.name: isPrototypeOf
sec-object.prototype.isprototypeof.summary: The isPrototypeOf() method checks if an object exists in another object's prototype chain.
sec-object.prototype.isprototypeof.title: Object.prototype.isPrototypeOf()

sec-object.issealed.name: isSealed
sec-object.issealed.summary: The Object.isSealed() method determines if an object is sealed.
sec-object.issealed.title: Object.isSealed()

sec-object.keys.name: keys
sec-object.keys.summary: The Object.keys() method returns an array of a given object's own enumerable property names, iterated in the same order that a normal loop would.
sec-object.keys.title: Object.keys()

sec-object.preventextensions.name: preventExtensions
sec-object.preventextensions.summary: The Object.preventExtensions() method prevents new properties from ever being added to an object (i.e. prevents future extensions to the object).
sec-object.preventextensions.title: Object.preventExtensions()

sec-object.prototype.propertyisenumerabl.name: propertyIsEnumerable
sec-object.prototype.propertyisenumerabl.summary: The propertyIsEnumerable() method returns a Boolean indicating whether the specified property is enumerable and is the object's own property.
sec-object.prototype.propertyisenumerabl.title: Object.prototype.propertyIsEnumerable()

sec-object.seal.name: seal
sec-object.seal.summary: The Object.seal() method seals an object, preventing new properties from being added to it and marking all existing properties as non-configurable. Values of present properties can still be changed as long as they are writable.
sec-object.seal.title: Object.seal()

sec-object.setprototypeof.name: setPrototypeOf
sec-object.setprototypeof.summary: The Object.setPrototypeOf() method sets the prototype (i.e., the internal [[Prototype]] property) of a specified object to another object or null.
sec-object.setprototypeof.title: Object.setPrototypeOf()

sec-object.prototype.tolocalestring.name: toLocaleString
sec-object.prototype.tolocalestring.summary: The toLocaleString() method returns a string representing the object. This method is meant to be overridden by derived objects for locale-specific purposes.
sec-object.prototype.tolocalestring.title: Object.prototype.toLocaleString()

sec-object.prototype.tostring.name: toString
sec-object.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the object.
sec-object.prototype.tostring.title: Object.prototype.toString()

sec-object.prototype.valueof.name: valueOf
sec-object.prototype.valueof.summary: The valueOf() method returns the primitive value of the specified object.
sec-object.prototype.valueof.title: Object.prototype.valueOf()

sec-object.values.name: values
sec-object.values.summary: The Object.values() method returns an array of a given object's own enumerable property values, in the same order as that provided by a for...in loop. (The only difference is that a for...in loop enumerates properties in the prototype chain as well.)
sec-object.values.title: Object.values()

sec-object-objects.name: Object
sec-object-objects.summary: The Object class represents one of JavaScript's data types. It is used to store various keyed collections and more complex entities. Objects can be created using the Object() constructor or the object initializer / literal syntax.
sec-object-objects.title: Object

sec-promise-constructor.name: Promise
sec-promise-constructor.summary: The Promise constructor is primarily used to wrap functions that do not already support promises.

firefox.notes: Constructor requires a new operator since version 37.

firefox_android.notes: Constructor requires a new operator since version 37.

nodejs.notes: Constructor requires a new operator since version 4.

safari.notes: Constructor requires a new operator since version 10.

safari_ios.notes: Constructor requires a new operator since version 10.

sec-promise-constructor.title: Promise() constructor

sec-promise.all.name: all
sec-promise.all.summary: The Promise.all() method takes an iterable of promises as an input, and returns a single Promise that resolves to an array of the results of the input promises. This returned promise will resolve when all of the input's promises have resolved, or if the input iterable contains no promises. It rejects immediately upon any of the input promises rejecting or non-promises throwing an error, and will reject with this first rejection message / error.
sec-promise.all.title: Promise.all()

sec-promise.prototype.catch.name: catch
sec-promise.prototype.catch.summary: The catch() method returns a Promise and deals with rejected cases only. It behaves the same as calling Promise.prototype.then(undefined, onRejected) (in fact, calling obj.catch(onRejected) internally calls obj.then(undefined, onRejected)). This means that you have to provide an onRejected function even if you want to fall back to an undefined result value - for example obj.catch(() => {}).
sec-promise.prototype.catch.title: Promise.prototype.catch()

sec-promise.prototype.finally.name: finally
sec-promise.prototype.finally.summary: The finally() method returns a Promise. When the promise is settled, i.e either fulfilled or rejected, the specified callback function is executed. This provides a way for code to be run whether the promise was fulfilled successfully or rejected once the Promise has been dealt with.
sec-promise.prototype.finally.title: Promise.prototype.finally()

sec-promise.race.name: race
sec-promise.race.summary: The Promise.race() method returns a promise that fulfills or rejects as soon as one of the promises in an iterable fulfills or rejects, with the value or reason from that promise.
sec-promise.race.title: Promise.race()

sec-promise.reject.name: reject
sec-promise.reject.summary: The Promise.reject() method returns a Promise object that is rejected with a given reason.
sec-promise.reject.title: Promise.reject()

sec-promise.resolve.name: resolve
sec-promise.resolve.summary: The Promise.resolve() method returns a Promise object that is resolved with a given value. If the value is a promise, that promise is returned; if the value is a thenable (i.e. has a "then" method), the returned promise will "follow" that thenable, adopting its eventual state; otherwise the returned promise will be fulfilled with the value. This function flattens nested layers of promise-like objects (e.g. a promise that resolves to a promise that resolves to something) into a single layer.
sec-promise.resolve.title: Promise.resolve()

sec-promise.prototype.then.name: then
sec-promise.prototype.then.summary: The then() method returns a Promise. It takes up to two arguments: callback functions for the success and failure cases of the Promise.
sec-promise.prototype.then.title: Promise.prototype.then()

sec-promise-objects.name: Promise
sec-promise-objects.summary: The Promise object represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation, and its resulting value.
sec-promise-objects.title: Promise

sec-proxy-constructor.name: Proxy
sec-proxy-constructor.summary: The Proxy() constructor is used to create Proxy objects.
sec-proxy-constructor.title: Proxy() constructor

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: apply
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.apply() method is a trap for a function call.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.apply()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: construct
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.construct() method is a trap for the new operator. In order for the new operation to be valid on the resulting Proxy object, the target used to initialize the proxy must itself have a [[Construct]] internal method (i.e. new target must be valid).
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.construct()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: defineProperty
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.defineProperty() method is a trap for Object.defineProperty().
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.defineProperty()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: deleteProperty
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.deleteProperty() method is a trap for the delete operator.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.deleteProperty()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: get
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.get() method is a trap for getting a property value.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.get()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: getOwnPropertyDescriptor
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.getOwnPropertyDescriptor() method is a trap for Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor().
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.getOwnPropertyDescriptor()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: getPrototypeOf
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.getPrototypeOf() method is a trap for the [[GetPrototypeOf]] internal method.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.getPrototypeOf()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: has
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.has() method is a trap for the in operator.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.has()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: isExtensible
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.isExtensible() method is a trap for Object.isExtensible().
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.isExtensible()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: ownKeys
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.ownKeys() method is a trap for Reflect.ownKeys().

firefox.notes: In Firefox 42, the implementation got updated to reflect the final ES2015 specification: The result is now checked if it is an array and if the array elements are either of type string or of type symbol. Enumerating duplicate own property names is not a failure anymore.

firefox_android.notes: In Firefox 42, the implementation got updated to reflect the final ES2015 specification: The result is now checked if it is an array and if the array elements are either of type string or of type symbol. Enumerating duplicate own property names is not a failure anymore.

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: preventExtensions
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.preventExtensions() method is a trap for Object.preventExtensions().
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.preventExtensions()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: set
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.set() method is a trap for setting a property value.
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.set()

sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.name: setPrototypeOf
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.summary: The handler.setPrototypeOf() method is a trap for Object.setPrototypeOf().
sec-proxy-object-internal-methods-and-in.title: handler.setPrototypeOf()

sec-proxy.revocable.name: revocable
sec-proxy.revocable.summary: The Proxy.revocable() method is used to create a revocable Proxy object.
sec-proxy.revocable.title: Proxy.revocable()

sec-proxy-objects.name: Proxy
sec-proxy-objects.summary: The Proxy object enables you to create a proxy for another object, which can intercept and redefine fundamental operations for that object.
sec-proxy-objects.title: Proxy

sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.name: RangeError
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.summary: The RangeError object indicates an error when a value is not in the set or range of allowed values.
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.title: RangeError

sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.name: ReferenceError
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.summary: The ReferenceError object represents an error when a non-existent variable is referenced.
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.title: ReferenceError

sec-reflect.apply.name: apply
sec-reflect.apply.summary: The static Reflect.apply() method calls a target function with arguments as specified.
sec-reflect.apply.title: Reflect.apply()

sec-reflect.construct.name: construct
sec-reflect.construct.summary: The static Reflect.construct() method acts like the new operator, but as a function. It is equivalent to calling new target(...args). It gives also the added option to specify a different prototype.
sec-reflect.construct.title: Reflect.construct()

sec-reflect.defineproperty.name: defineProperty
sec-reflect.defineproperty.summary: The static Reflect.defineProperty() method is like Object.defineProperty() but returns a Boolean.
sec-reflect.defineproperty.title: Reflect.defineProperty()

sec-reflect.deleteproperty.name: deleteProperty
sec-reflect.deleteproperty.summary: The static Reflect.deleteProperty() method allows to delete properties. It is like the delete operator as a function.
sec-reflect.deleteproperty.title: Reflect.deleteProperty()

sec-reflect.get.name: get
sec-reflect.get.summary: The static Reflect.get() method works like getting a property from an object (target[propertyKey]) as a function.
sec-reflect.get.title: Reflect.get()

sec-reflect.getownpropertydescriptor.name: getOwnPropertyDescriptor
sec-reflect.getownpropertydescriptor.summary: The static Reflect.getOwnPropertyDescriptor() method is similar to Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(). It returns a property descriptor of the given property if it exists on the object, undefined otherwise.
sec-reflect.getownpropertydescriptor.title: Reflect.getOwnPropertyDescriptor()

sec-reflect.getprototypeof.name: getPrototypeOf
sec-reflect.getprototypeof.summary: The static Reflect.getPrototypeOf() method is almost the same method as Object.getPrototypeOf(). It returns the prototype (i.e. the value of the internal [[Prototype]] property) of the specified object.
sec-reflect.getprototypeof.title: Reflect.getPrototypeOf()

sec-reflect.has.name: has
sec-reflect.has.summary: The static Reflect.has() method works like the in operator as a function.
sec-reflect.has.title: Reflect.has()

sec-reflect.isextensible.name: isExtensible
sec-reflect.isextensible.summary: The static Reflect.isExtensible() method determines if an object is extensible (whether it can have new properties added to it). It is similar to Object.isExtensible(), but with some differences.
sec-reflect.isextensible.title: Reflect.isExtensible()

sec-reflect.ownkeys.name: ownKeys
sec-reflect.ownkeys.summary: The static Reflect.ownKeys() method returns an array of the target object's own property keys.
sec-reflect.ownkeys.title: Reflect.ownKeys()

sec-reflect.preventextensions.name: preventExtensions
sec-reflect.preventextensions.summary: The static Reflect.preventExtensions() method prevents new properties from ever being added to an object (i.e., prevents future extensions to the object).
sec-reflect.preventextensions.title: Reflect.preventExtensions()

sec-reflect.set.name: set
sec-reflect.set.summary: The static Reflect.set() method works like setting a property on an object.
sec-reflect.set.title: Reflect.set()

sec-reflect.setprototypeof.name: setPrototypeOf
sec-reflect.setprototypeof.summary: The static Reflect.setPrototypeOf() method is the same method as Object.setPrototypeOf(), except for its return type. It sets the prototype (i.e., the internal [[Prototype]] property) of a specified object to another object or to null, and returns true if the operation was successful, or false otherwise
sec-reflect.setprototypeof.title: Reflect.setPrototypeOf()

sec-reflect-object.name: Reflect
sec-reflect-object.summary: Reflect is a built-in object that provides methods for interceptable JavaScript operations. The methods are the same as those of proxy handlers. Reflect is not a function object, so it's not constructible.
sec-reflect-object.title: Reflect

sec-regexp-constructor.name: RegExp
sec-regexp-constructor.summary: The RegExp constructor creates a regular expression object for matching text with a pattern.
sec-regexp-constructor.title: RegExp() constructor

sec-regexp.prototype.exec.name: exec
sec-regexp.prototype.exec.summary: The exec() method executes a search for a match in a specified string. Returns a result array, or null.
sec-regexp.prototype.exec.title: RegExp.prototype.exec()

sec-get-regexp.prototype.flags.name: flags
sec-get-regexp.prototype.flags.summary: The flags property returns a string consisting of the flags of the current regular expression object.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.flags.title: RegExp.prototype.flags

sec-get-regexp.prototype.global.name: global
sec-get-regexp.prototype.global.summary: The global property indicates whether or not the "g" flag is used with the regular expression. global is a read-only property of an individual regular expression instance.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.global.title: RegExp.prototype.global

sec-get-regexp.prototype.ignorecase.name: ignoreCase
sec-get-regexp.prototype.ignorecase.summary: The ignoreCase property indicates whether or not the "i" flag is used with the regular expression. ignoreCase is a read-only property of an individual regular expression instance.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.ignorecase.title: RegExp.prototype.ignoreCase

sec-properties-of-regexp-instances.name: lastIndex
sec-properties-of-regexp-instances.summary: The lastIndex is a read/write integer property of regular expression instances that specifies the index at which to start the next match.
sec-properties-of-regexp-instances.title: RegExpInstance.lastIndex

sec-get-regexp.prototype.multiline.name: multiline
sec-get-regexp.prototype.multiline.summary: The multiline property indicates whether or not the "m" flag is used with the regular expression. multiline is a read-only property of an individual regular expression instance.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.multiline.title: RegExp.prototype.multiline

sec-get-regexp.prototype.source.name: source
sec-get-regexp.prototype.source.summary: The source property returns a String containing the source text of the regexp object, and it doesn't contain the two forward slashes on both sides and any flags.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.source.title: RegExp.prototype.source

sec-get-regexp.prototype.sticky.name: sticky
sec-get-regexp.prototype.sticky.summary: The sticky property reflects whether or not the search is sticky (searches in strings only from the index indicated by the lastIndex property of this regular expression). sticky is a read-only property of an individual regular expression object.
sec-get-regexp.prototype.sticky.title: RegExp.prototype.sticky

sec-regexp.prototype.test.name: test
sec-regexp.prototype.test.summary: The test() method executes a search for a match between a regular expression and a specified string. Returns true or false.
sec-regexp.prototype.test.title: RegExp.prototype.test()

sec-regexp.prototype.tostring.name: toString

sec-string-constructor.name: String
sec-string-constructor.summary: The String constructor is used to create a new String object. It performs type conversion when called as a function, rather than as a constructor, which is usually more useful.

sec-string.prototype.charat.name: charAt
sec-string.prototype.charat.summary: The String object's charAt() method returns a new string consisting of the single UTF-16 code unit located at the specified offset into the string.

sec-string.prototype.charcodeat.name: charCodeAt
sec-string.prototype.charcodeat.summary: The charCodeAt() method returns an integer between 0 and 65535 representing the UTF-16 code unit at the given index.
sec-string.prototype.charcodeat.title: String.prototype.charCodeAt()

sec-string.prototype.codepointat.name: codePointAt
sec-string.prototype.codepointat.summary: The codePointAt() method returns a non-negative integer that is the Unicode code point value.
sec-string.prototype.codepointat.title: String.prototype.codePointAt()

sec-string.prototype.concat.name: concat
sec-string.prototype.concat.summary: The concat() method concatenates the string arguments to the calling string and returns a new string.
sec-string.prototype.concat.title: String.prototype.concat()

sec-string.prototype.endswith.name: endsWith
sec-string.prototype.endswith.summary: The endsWith() method determines whether a string ends with the characters of a specified string, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-string.prototype.endswith.title: String.prototype.endsWith()

sec-string.fromcharcode.name: fromCharCode
sec-string.fromcharcode.summary: The static String.fromCharCode() method returns a string created from the specified sequence of UTF-16 code units.
sec-string.fromcharcode.title: String.fromCharCode()

sec-string.fromcodepoint.name: fromCodePoint
sec-string.fromcodepoint.summary: The static String.fromCodePoint() method returns a string created by using the specified sequence of code points.
sec-string.fromcodepoint.title: String.fromCodePoint()

sec-string.prototype.includes.name: includes
sec-string.prototype.includes.summary: The includes() method determines whether one string may be found within another string, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-string.prototype.includes.title: String.prototype.includes()

sec-string.prototype.indexof.name: indexOf
sec-string.prototype.indexof.summary: The indexOf() method returns the index within the calling String object of the first occurrence of the specified value, starting the search at fromIndex. Returns -1 if the value is not found.
sec-string.prototype.indexof.title: String.prototype.indexOf()

sec-string.prototype.lastindexof.name: lastIndexOf
sec-string.prototype.lastindexof.summary: The lastIndexOf() method returns the index within the calling String object of the last occurrence of the specified value, searching backwards from fromIndex. Returns -1 if the value is not found.
sec-string.prototype.lastindexof.title: String.prototype.lastIndexOf()

sec-properties-of-string-instances-lengt.name: length
sec-properties-of-string-instances-lengt.summary: The length property of a String object contains the length of the string, in UTF-16 code units. length is a read-only data property of string instances.

sec-string.prototype.localecompare.name: localeCompare
sec-string.prototype.localecompare.summary: The localeCompare() method returns a number indicating whether a reference string comes before, or after, or is the same as the given string in sort order.
sec-string.prototype.localecompare.title: String.prototype.localeCompare()

sec-string.prototype.match.name: match
sec-string.prototype.match.summary: The match() method retrieves the result of matching a string against a regular expression.
sec-string.prototype.match.title: String.prototype.match()

sec-string.prototype.matchall.name: matchAll
sec-string.prototype.matchall.summary: The matchAll() method returns an iterator of all results matching a string against a regular expression, including capturing groups.
sec-string.prototype.matchall.title: String.prototype.matchAll()

sec-string.prototype.normalize.name: normalize
sec-string.prototype.normalize.summary: The normalize() method returns the Unicode Normalization Form of the string.
sec-string.prototype.normalize.title: String.prototype.normalize()

sec-string.prototype.padend.name: padEnd
sec-string.prototype.padend.summary: The padEnd() method pads the current string with a given string (repeated, if needed) so that the resulting string reaches a given length. The padding is applied from the end of the current string.
sec-string.prototype.padend.title: String.prototype.padEnd()

sec-string.prototype.padstart.name: padStart
sec-string.prototype.padstart.summary: The padStart() method pads the current string with another string (multiple times, if needed) until the resulting string reaches the given length.
sec-string.prototype.padstart.title: String.prototype.padStart()

sec-string.raw.name: raw
sec-string.raw.summary: The static String.raw() method is a tag function of template literals. This is similar to the r prefix in Python, or the @ prefix in C# for string literals. (But it is not identical; see explanations in this issue.) It's used to get the raw string form of template strings, that is, substitutions (e.g. ${foo}) are processed, but escapes (e.g. \n) are not.
sec-string.raw.title: String.raw()

sec-string.prototype.repeat.name: repeat
sec-string.prototype.repeat.summary: The repeat() method constructs and returns a new string which contains the specified number of copies of the string on which it was called, concatenated together.
sec-string.prototype.repeat.title: String.prototype.repeat()

sec-string.prototype.replace.name: replace
sec-string.prototype.replace.summary: The replace() method returns a new string with some or all matches of a pattern replaced by a replacement.
sec-string.prototype.replace.title: String.prototype.replace()

sec-string.prototype.search.name: search
sec-string.prototype.search.summary: The search() method executes a search for a match between a regular expression and this String object.
sec-string.prototype.search.title: String.prototype.search()

sec-string.prototype.slice.name: slice
sec-string.prototype.slice.summary: The slice() method extracts a section of a string and returns it as a new string, without modifying the original string.
sec-string.prototype.slice.title: String.prototype.slice()

sec-string.prototype.split.name: split
sec-string.prototype.split.summary: The split() method divides a String into an ordered list of substrings, puts these substrings into an array, and returns the array.  The division is done by searching for a pattern; where the pattern is provided as the first parameter in the method's call.
sec-string.prototype.split.title: String.prototype.split()

sec-string.prototype.startswith.name: startsWith
sec-string.prototype.startswith.summary: The startsWith() method determines whether a string begins with the characters of a specified string, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-string.prototype.startswith.title: String.prototype.startsWith()

sec-string.prototype.substring.name: substring
sec-string.prototype.substring.summary: The substring() method returns the part of the string between the start and end indexes, or to the end of the string.
sec-string.prototype.substring.title: String.prototype.substring()

sec-string.prototype.tolocalelowercase.name: toLocaleLowerCase
sec-string.prototype.tolocalelowercase.summary: The toLocaleLowerCase() method returns the calling string value converted to lower case, according to any locale-specific case mappings.

sec-string.prototype.tolocaleuppercase.name: toLocaleUpperCase
sec-string.prototype.tolocaleuppercase.summary: The toLocaleUpperCase() method returns the calling string value converted to upper case, according to any locale-specific case mappings.
sec-string.prototype.tolocaleuppercase.title: String.prototype.toLocaleUpperCase()

sec-string.prototype.tolowercase.name: toLowerCase
sec-string.prototype.tolowercase.summary: The toLowerCase() method returns the calling string value converted to lower case.
sec-string.prototype.tolowercase.title: String.prototype.toLowerCase()

sec-string.prototype.tostring.name: toString
sec-string.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified object.

sec-string.prototype.touppercase.name: toUpperCase
sec-string.prototype.touppercase.summary: The toUpperCase() method returns the calling string value converted to uppercase (the value will be converted to a string if it isn't one).

sec-string.prototype.trim.title: String.prototype.trim()

sec-string.prototype.trimend.name: trimEnd

sec-string.prototype.trimstart.name: trimStart

sec-string.prototype.trimstart.title: String.prototype.trimStart()

sec-symbol.split.name: split

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.map.name: map
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.map.summary: The map() method creates a new typed array with the results of calling a provided function on every element in this typed array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.map(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.

sec-%typedarray%.of.name: of

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduce.name: reduce

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduceright.title: TypedArray.prototype.reduceRight()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reverse.name: reverse

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.set-array-off.name: set

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.slice.name: slice

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.some.name: some

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tolocalestrin.summary: The toLocaleString() method returns a string representing the elements of the typed array. sec-assignment-operators.title: Bitwise AND assignment (&=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: bitwise_or_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The bitwise OR assignment operator (|=) uses the binary representation of both operands, does a bitwise OR operation on them and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Bitwise OR assignment (|=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: bitwise_xor_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The bitwise XOR assignment operator (^=) uses the binary representation of both operands, does a bitwise XOR operation on them and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Bitwise XOR assignment (^=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: division_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The division assignment operator (/=) divides a variable by the value of the right operand and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Division assignment (/=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: left_shift_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The left shift assignment operator (<<=) moves the specified amount of bits to the left and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Left shift assignment (<<=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: multiplication_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The multiplication assignment operator (*=) multiplies a variable by the value of the right operand and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Multiplication assignment (*=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: remainder_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The remainder assignment operator (%=) divides a variable by the value of the right operand and assigns the remainder to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Remainder assignment (%=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: right_shift_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The right shift assignment operator (>>=) moves the specified amount of bits to the right and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Right shift assignment (>>=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: substraction_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The subtraction assignment operator (-=) subtracts the value of the right operand from a variable and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Subtraction assignment (-=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: unsigned_right_shift_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The unsigned right shift assignment operator (>>>=) moves the specified amount of bits to the right and assigns the result to the variable.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Unsigned right shift assignment (>>>=)

sec-async-function-definitions.name: async_function_expression
sec-async-function-definitions.summary: The async function keyword can be used to define async functions inside expressions.
sec-async-function-definitions.title: async function expression

sec-async-function-definitions.name: await
sec-async-function-definitions.summary: The await operator is used to wait for a Promise. It can only be used inside an async function.
sec-async-function-definitions.title: await

sec-async-function-definitions.name: async_function
sec-async-function-definitions.summary: An async function is a function declared with the async keyword. Async functions are instances of the AsyncFunction constructor, and the await keyword is permitted within them. The async and await keywords enable asynchronous, promise-based behavior to be written in a cleaner style, avoiding the need to explicitly configure promise chains.
sec-async-function-definitions.title: async function

prod-BitwiseANDExpression.name: bitwise_and
prod-BitwiseANDExpression.summary: The bitwise AND operator (&) returns a 1 in each bit position for which the corresponding bits of both operands are 1s.
prod-BitwiseANDExpression.title: Bitwise AND (&)

sec-bitwise-not-operator.name: bitwise_not
sec-bitwise-not-operator.summary: The bitwise NOT operator (~) inverts the bits of its operand.
sec-bitwise-not-operator.title: Bitwise NOT (~)

prod-BitwiseORExpression.name: bitwise_or
prod-BitwiseORExpression.summary: The bitwise OR operator (|) returns a 1 in each bit position for which the corresponding bits of either or both operands are 1s.
prod-BitwiseORExpression.title: Bitwise OR (|)

prod-BitwiseXORExpression.name: bitwise_xor
prod-BitwiseXORExpression.summary: The bitwise XOR operator (^) returns a 1 in each bit position for which the corresponding bits of either but not both operands are 1s.
prod-BitwiseXORExpression.title: Bitwise XOR (^)

sec-comma-operator.name: comma
sec-comma-operator.summary: The comma operator (,) evaluates each of its operands (from left to right) and returns the value of the last operand. This lets you create a compound expression in which multiple expressions are evaluated, with the compound expression's final value being the value of the rightmost of its member expressions. This is commonly used to provide multiple parameters to a for loop.
sec-comma-operator.title: Comma operator (,)

sec-conditional-operator.name: conditional
sec-conditional-operator.summary: The conditional (ternary) operator is the only JavaScript operator that takes three operands: a condition followed by a question mark (?), then an expression to execute if the condition is truthy followed by a colon (:), and finally the expression to execute if the condition is falsy.
sec-conditional-operator.title: Conditional (ternary) operator

sec-postfix-decrement-operator.name: decrement
sec-postfix-decrement-operator.summary: The decrement operator (--) decrements (subtracts one from) its operand and returns a value.
sec-postfix-decrement-operator.title: Decrement (--)

sec-delete-operator.name: delete
sec-delete-operator.summary: The JavaScript delete operator removes a property from an object; if no more references to the same property are held, it is eventually released automatically.
sec-delete-operator.title: delete operator

sec-destructuring-assignment.name: destructuring
sec-destructuring-assignment.summary: The destructuring assignment syntax is a JavaScript expression that makes it possible to unpack values from arrays, or properties from objects, into distinct variables.

firefox.notes: Firefox provided a non-standard destructuring implementation from Firefox 2 to 40.

firefox_android.notes: Firefox provided a non-standard destructuring implementation from Firefox 2 to 40.

sec-destructuring-assignment.title: Destructuring assignment

sec-multiplicative-operators.name: division
sec-multiplicative-operators.summary: The division operator (/) produces the quotient of its operands where the left operand is the dividend and the right operand is the divisor.
sec-multiplicative-operators.title: Division (/)

sec-multiplicative-operators.name: multiplication
sec-multiplicative-operators.summary: The multiplication operator (*) produces the product of the operands.
sec-multiplicative-operators.title: Multiplication (*)

sec-multiplicative-operators.name: remainder
sec-multiplicative-operators.summary: The remainder operator (%) returns the remainder left over when one operand is divided by a second operand. It always takes the sign of the dividend.
sec-multiplicative-operators.title: Remainder (%)

sec-equality-operators.name: equality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The equality operator (==) checks whether its two operands are equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the strict equality operator, it attempts to convert and compare operands that are of different types.
sec-equality-operators.title: Equality (==)

sec-equality-operators.name: inequality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The inequality operator (!=) checks whether its two operands are not equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the strict inequality operator, it attempts to convert and compare operands that are of different types.
sec-equality-operators.title: Inequality (!=)

sec-equality-operators.name: strict_equality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The strict equality operator (===) checks whether its two operands are equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the equality operator, the strict equality operator always considers operands of different types to be different.
sec-equality-operators.title: Strict equality (===)

sec-equality-operators.name: strict_inequality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The strict inequality operator (!==) checks whether its two operands are not equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the inequality operator, the strict inequality operator always considers operands of different types to be different.
sec-equality-operators.title: Strict inequality (!==)

sec-exp-operator.name: exponentiation
sec-exp-operator.summary: The exponentiation operator (**) returns the result of raising the first operand to the power of the second operand.
sec-exp-operator.title: Exponentiation (**)

sec-generator-function-definitions.name: function_star
sec-generator-function-definitions.summary: The function* keyword can be used to define a generator function inside an expression.
sec-generator-function-definitions.title: function* expression

sec-generator-function-definitions.name: generator_function
sec-generator-function-definitions.summary: The function* declaration (function keyword followed by an asterisk) defines a generator function, which returns a Generator object.
sec-generator-function-definitions.title: function*

sec-relational-operators.name: greater_than
sec-relational-operators.summary: The greater than operator (>) returns true if the left operand is greater than the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Greater than (>)

sec-relational-operators.name: greater_than_or_equal
sec-relational-operators.summary: The greater than or equal operator (>=) returns true if the left operand is greater than or equal to the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Greater than or equal (>=)

sec-relational-operators.name: in
sec-relational-operators.summary: The in operator returns true if the specified property is in the specified object or its prototype chain.
sec-relational-operators.title: in operator

sec-relational-operators.name: instanceof
sec-relational-operators.summary: The instanceof operator tests whether the prototype property of a constructor appears anywhere in the prototype chain of an object.
sec-relational-operators.title: instanceof

sec-relational-operators.name: less_than
sec-relational-operators.summary: The less than operator (<) returns true if the left operand is less than the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Less than (<)

sec-relational-operators.name: less_than_or_equal
sec-relational-operators.summary: The less than or equal operator (<=) returns true if the left operand is less than or equal to the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Less than or equal (<=)

sec-grouping-operator.name: grouping
sec-grouping-operator.summary: The grouping operator ( ) controls the precedence of evaluation in expressions.
sec-grouping-operator.title: Grouping operator ( )

sec-postfix-increment-operator.name: increment
sec-postfix-increment-operator.summary: The increment operator (++) increments (adds one to) its operand and returns a value.
sec-postfix-increment-operator.title: Increment (++)

prod-LogicalANDExpression.name: logical_and
prod-LogicalANDExpression.summary: The logical AND (&&) operator (logical conjunction) for a set of operands is true if and only if all of its operands are true. It is typically used with Boolean (logical) values. When it is, it returns a Boolean value. However, the && operator actually returns the value of one of the specified operands, so if this operator is used with non-Boolean values, it will return a non-Boolean value.
prod-LogicalANDExpression.title: Logical AND (&&)

sec-logical-not-operator.name: logical_not
sec-logical-not-operator.summary: The logical NOT (!) operator (logical complement, negation) takes truth to falsity and vice versa. It is typically used with Boolean (logical) values. When used with non-Boolean values, it returns false if its single operand can be converted to true; otherwise, returns true.
sec-logical-not-operator.title: Logical NOT (!)

prod-LogicalORExpression.name: logical_or
prod-LogicalORExpression.summary: The logical OR (||) operator (logical disjunction) for a set of operands is true if and only if one or more of its operands is true. It is typically used with Boolean (logical) values. When it is, it returns a Boolean value. However, the || operator actually returns the value of one of the specified operands, so if this operator is used with non-Boolean values, it will return a non-Boolean value.
prod-LogicalORExpression.title: Logical OR (||)

sec-new-operator.name: new
sec-new-operator.summary: The new operator lets developers create an instance of a user-defined object type or of one of the built-in object types that has a constructor function.
sec-new-operator.title: new operator

sec-built-in-function-objects.name: new_target
sec-built-in-function-objects.summary: The new.target pseudo-property lets you detect whether a function or constructor was called using the new operator. In constructors and functions invoked using the new operator, new.target returns a reference to the constructor or function. In normal function calls, new.target is undefined.
sec-built-in-function-objects.title: new.target

sec-object-initializer.name: object_initializer
sec-object-initializer.summary: Objects can be initialized using new Object(), Object.create(), or using the literal notation (initializer notation). An object initializer is a comma-delimited list of zero or more pairs of property names and associated values of an object, enclosed in curly braces ({}).
sec-object-initializer.title: Object initializer

sec-property-accessors.name: property_accessors
sec-property-accessors.summary: Property accessors provide access to an object's properties by using the dot notation or the bracket notation.
sec-property-accessors.title: Property accessors

sec-subtraction-operator-minus.name: subtraction
sec-subtraction-operator-minus.summary: The subtraction operator (-) subtracts the two operands, producing their difference.
sec-subtraction-operator-minus.title: Subtraction (-)

sec-super-keyword.name: super
sec-super-keyword.summary: The super keyword is used to access and call functions on an object's parent.
sec-super-keyword.title: super

sec-this-keyword.name: this
sec-this-keyword.summary: A function's this keyword behaves a little differently in JavaScript compared to other languages. It also has some differences between strict mode and non-strict mode.
sec-this-keyword.title: this

sec-typeof-operator.name: typeof
sec-typeof-operator.summary: The typeof operator returns a string indicating the type of the unevaluated operand.
sec-typeof-operator.title: typeof

sec-unary-minus-operator.name: unary_negation
sec-unary-minus-operator.summary: The unary negation operator (-) precedes its operand and negates it.
sec-unary-minus-operator.title: Unary negation (-)

sec-unary-plus-operator.name: unary_plus
sec-unary-plus-operator.summary: The unary plus operator (+) precedes its operand and evaluates to its operand but attempts to convert it into a number, if it isn't already.
sec-unary-plus-operator.title: Unary plus (+)

sec-void-operator.name: void
sec-void-operator.summary: The void operator evaluates the given expression and then returns undefined.
sec-void-operator.title: void operator

prod-YieldExpression.name: yield
prod-YieldExpression.summary: The yield keyword is used to pause and resume a generator function (function* or legacy generator function).

notes: Starting with Firefox 33, the parsing of the yield expression has been updated to conform with the ES2015 specification.
Starting with Firefox 29, an IteratorResult object returned for completed generator function.

prod-YieldExpression.title: yield

sec-generator-function-definitions-runti.name: yield_star
sec-generator-function-definitions-runti.summary: The yield* expression is used to delegate to another generator or iterable object.

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 33, the parsing of the yield expression has been updated to conform with the ES2015 specification.

firefox_android.notes: Starting with Firefox 33, the parsing of the yield expression has been updated to conform with the ES2015 specification.

sec-generator-function-definitions-runti.title: yield*

sec-block.name: block
sec-block.summary: A block statement (or compound statement in other languages) is used to group zero or more statements. The block is delimited by a pair of braces ("curly brackets") and may optionally be labelled:
sec-block.title: block

sec-break-statement.name: break
sec-break-statement.summary: The break statement terminates the current loop, switch, or label statement and transfers program control to the statement following the terminated statement.
sec-break-statement.title: break

sec-let-and-const-declarations.name: const
sec-let-and-const-declarations.summary: Constants are block-scoped, much like variables defined using the let keyword. The value of a constant can't be changed through reassignment, and it can't be redeclared.

notes: Prior to Firefox 13, const is implemented, but re-assignment is not failing.

sec-let-and-const-declarations.summary: The let statement declares a block-scoped local variable, optionally initializing it to a value.

sec-continue-statement.name: continue
sec-continue-statement.summary: The continue statement terminates execution of the statements in the current iteration of the current or labeled loop, and continues execution of the loop with the next iteration.
sec-continue-statement.title: continue

sec-debugger-statement.name: debugger
sec-debugger-statement.summary: The debugger statement invokes any available debugging functionality, such as setting a breakpoint. If no debugging functionality is available, this statement has no effect.
sec-debugger-statement.title: debugger

sec-do-while-statement.name: do_while
sec-do-while-statement.summary: The do...while statement creates a loop that executes a specified statement until the test condition evaluates to false. The condition is evaluated after executing the statement, resulting in the specified statement executing at least once.
sec-do-while-statement.title: do...while

sec-empty-statement.name: empty
sec-empty-statement.summary: An empty statement is used to provide no statement, although the JavaScript syntax would expect one.
sec-empty-statement.title: empty

sec-exports.name: namespace
sec-exports.summary: The export statement is used when creating JavaScript modules to export live bindings to functions, objects, or primitive values from the module so they can be used by other programs with the import statement. Bindings that are exported can still be modified locally; when imported, although they can only be read by the importing module the value updates whenever it is updated by the exporting module.
sec-exports.title: export

Bindings that are exported can still be modified locally; when imported, although they can only be read by the importing module the value updates whenever it is updated by the exporting module.

sec-for-statement.name: for
sec-for-statement.summary: The for statement creates a loop that consists of three optional expressions, enclosed in parentheses and separated by semicolons, followed by a statement (usually a block statement) to be executed in the loop.
sec-for-statement.title: for

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.name: for_await_of
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.summary: The for await...of statement creates a loop iterating over async iterable objects as well as on sync iterables, including: built-in String, Array, Array-like objects (e.g., arguments or NodeList), TypedArray, Map, Set, and user-defined async/sync iterables. It invokes a custom iteration hook with statements to be executed for the value of each distinct property of the object. Like await operator, the statement can only be used inside an async function.
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.title: for await...of

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.name: for_in
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.summary: The for...in statement iterates over all enumerable properties of an object that are keyed by strings (ignoring ones keyed by Symbols), including inherited enumerable properties.
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.title: for...in

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.name: for_of
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.summary: The for...of statement creates a loop iterating over iterable objects, including: built-in String, Array, array-like objects (e.g., arguments or NodeList), TypedArray, Map, Set, and user-defined iterables. It invokes a custom iteration hook with statements to be executed for the value of each distinct property of the object.

firefox.notes: Prior to Firefox 51, using the for...of loop construct with the const keyword threw a SyntaxError ("missing = in const declaration").

firefox_android.notes: Prior to Firefox 51, using the for...of loop construct with the const keyword threw a SyntaxError ("missing = in const declaration").

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.title: for...of

sec-if-statement.name: if_else
sec-if-statement.summary: The if statement executes a statement if a specified condition is truthy. If the condition is falsy, another statement can be executed.
sec-if-statement.title: if...else

sec-imports.name: import
sec-imports.summary: The static import statement is used to import read only live bindings which are exported by another module.

nodejs.notes: Modules must either have a filename ending in .mjs, or the nearest parent package.json file must contain "type": "module". See Node's ECMAScript Modules documentation for more details.

sec-imports.title: import

sec-labelled-statements.name: label
sec-labelled-statements.summary: The labeled statement can be used with break or continue statements. It is prefixing a statement with an identifier which you can refer to.
sec-labelled-statements.title: label

sec-return-statement.name: return
sec-return-statement.summary: The return statement ends function execution and specifies a value to be returned to the function caller.
sec-return-statement.title: return

sec-switch-statement.name: switch
sec-switch-statement.summary: The switch statement evaluates an expression, matching the expression's value to a case clause, and executes statements associated with that case, as well as statements in cases that follow the matching case.
sec-switch-statement.title: switch

sec-throw-statement.name: throw
sec-throw-statement.summary: The throw statement throws a user-defined exception. Execution of the current function will stop (the statements after throw won't be executed), and control will be passed to the first catch block in the call stack. If no catch block exists among caller functions, the program will terminate.
sec-throw-statement.title: throw

sec-try-statement.name: try_catch
sec-try-statement.summary: The try...catch statement marks a block of statements to try and specifies a response should an exception be thrown.
sec-try-statement.title: try...catch

sec-variable-statement.name: var
sec-variable-statement.summary: The var statement declares a function-scoped or globally-scoped variable, optionally initializing it to a value.
sec-variable-statement.title: var

sec-while-statement.name: while
sec-while-statement.summary: The while statement creates a loop that executes a specified statement as long as the test condition evaluates to true. The condition is evaluated before executing the statement.
sec-while-statement.title: while
